@flexiarg peeragogy/discerning-a-pattern
@title Notice the Repetition First, Name It Carefully Second
@keywords pattern-detection, vocabulary, language-attention, naming, alexander, repetition
@audience pattern authors, peer-learning practitioners
@tone reflective
@style meta-pattern
@references [peeragogy/pattern-language peeragogy/creating-a-guide pattern-coherence/applicability-signals]

! conclusion: A peeragogical pattern starts as a noticed repetition: something that happens often enough across peer-learning situations that it deserves a shared name.  The discernment work is twofold — first, attending to language and behaviour closely enough to spot the repetition at all; second, naming it without over-claiming what the repetition means.  Most candidate patterns die in the second step, when the namer rushes from "I see this pattern" to "and therefore the participants are X."
  + context: Patterns are not invented; they are discerned.  The handbook draws on Alexander's framing — language use is what we have to go on analytically, and patterns surface from that close attention to use.  In peer-learning, candidate patterns appear as recurring forms: shared interests in introductions, shared shapes in how groups organise sessions, shared failures in how groups onboard newcomers.  The discernment skill is a kind of meta-awareness of language — close enough to see repetition, careful enough not to over-interpret what the repetition means.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: noticing repetition ↔ resisting interpretation.
    Real: the same close attention that lets a pattern-spotter see recurrence also tempts them to attribute meaning the recurrence does not yet support.  Both moves draw on the same alertness, but only the first is reliable.
    Irreducible: a noticed pattern cannot be both raw observation and interpreted significance simultaneously.  The discernment process must hold these two stages apart, even when the noticer wants to collapse them into one insight.
    Active: the pull recurs every time a pattern-spotter sees a third instance and feels the urge to declare what it means.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Note-then-defer: record the noticed repetition in the smallest possible form (occurrence, context, what was repeated) and resist naming what it implies for at least a few more instances.
    (2) Title-and-describe: once the repetition is robust enough to deserve a name, write the title first and the description second.  The title forces commitment to a specific pattern shape; the description tests whether that shape holds across the instances.
    (3) Hedge interpretation: when describing what the pattern says about the participants or the situation, use "might" and "may" rather than "indicates" until the meaning has been tested across more instances.
    (4) Submit for collaborative refinement: a discerned pattern is sharpened by other practitioners trying to break it on their own data; treat the first articulation as a draft, not a finding.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: pattern claims are grounded in named instances, and interpretive claims are kept separate from observational claims.  Failing when: a single observation is promoted to a pattern, or a pattern's interpretation is asserted with confidence that the underlying instances do not support.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Insight inflation: each noticed coincidence becomes a "pattern" without surviving repeated test.
    - Premature meaning: the pattern description tells the reader what the pattern signifies before establishing that the pattern exists.
    - Vocabulary churn: pattern names proliferate and rename without stabilising into a usable language (see peeragogy/pattern-language).
    - Loss of source: pattern descriptions drift from the situations that grounded them, becoming abstract advice.
